content.description: Right of the crack, head up the slab on delicate holds.  Route goes up and moves slightly to the right.

This route starts with a slightly overhanging hand crack in an alcove.  The jams are solid but the right wall makes the moves to the lip a little awkward.  Once above the overhang the crack widens and the difficulty eases.
content.location: The left crack on the left wall.

content.description: A few stretches of interesting climbing broken up with ledge scrambling. The climb starts with an short face problem to a large ledge (easy avoided by scrambling to the left). Next is a left leaning finger crack in a right facing dihedral. After some more scrambling there is a thin face up to a recessed bucket followed by more scrambling. The final face leads up to a pair of bolts set back from the edge.
content.protection: Best as a top rope problem, but it can be led with gear up to 2.5 inches. Bolted anchor can be reached by a trail to the right or from the parking lot behind the wall.
content.location: Follows a series of cracks and weaknesses up the North facing face on right, away from the other routes.

content.description:
Easy climbing left of a huge slabby boulder gains the crack.  Lieback and jam the clean crack while utilizing good holds on the face.  The final moves involve bypassing a flake with a few mildly intimidating undercling moves.

A 5.10 TR variation climbs the left edge of the boulder on the right rather that the blocky corner.
content.protection: Gear to 2.5". Doubles of 0.75-2 strongly recommended. Bolted anchor
content.location: The right crack on the left wall.

content.description: Low angle hand crack great for teaching people basic crack climbing.
content.location: On the right side of Barney's Rubble, directly behind the Slice of Pie boulder

content.description: good thin slab climbing, crux comes near the top when you need to make a smeary move to grab a good horizontal.
content.protection: Shares an anchor with 5.6 crack, you can place a small cam as a directional in a horizontal near top
content.location: The faceclimb to the right of 5.8 crack and to the left of 5.6 crack
